                        <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 50.&#8212;<name type="person">Private John B. Talbot</name>, <name type="organization">Co. H, 6th Mich. Cav.</name>; age 23; admitted <date type="admit" when="1964-02-13">Feb. 13, 1864</date>, with
                                pleuro-pneumonia, following measles.  Died <date type="death" when="1864-02-29"></date>29th.   <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination: The lower lobe of the right lung was hepatized
                                        red and presented on section a number of small superficial
                                        abscesses.  [<hi rend="italic">Specimen</hi> 345, Med. Sec., <name type="hospital" key="431">Army Medical Museum</name>.]  The pleura was thickened. The kidneys were fatty.&#8212;<hi rend="italic"><name type="person" key="134">Surgeon E. Bentley</name>, <name type="organization" key="132">U. S. Vols.</name>, <name type="hospital" key="189">Third Division Hospital</name>, <name type="place">Alexandria, Va.</name></hi></p>                        
